About two months ago I had the great experience to go to Poland and travel with Yosef Lewkowicz, a Holocaust survivor, to multiple camps that he had been forced to be at and other important sites in Poland. On this day Jews observe Yom HaShoah in remembrance of the Holocaust because it marks the anniversary of the Warsaw Ghetto uprising. The last picture in here is from the cemetery next to the last part of the remaining wall in Warsaw. While I haven’t been actively posting about it, over the past few months I’ve become more and more connected to my Jewish roots. Knowing my great grandfather lived in Poland made this trip emotional but even more impactful was being able to travel with Yosef and hear all of his incredible stories. I did not expect to end up playing for everyone, especially not while they walk towards the gas chambers at the camp where Yosef lost his entire family. This was probably the hardest and most emotional playing experience I will ever have, even more so because I had to walk it alone before everyone else behind me. In the second slide you get to directly hear Yosef and his wishes. The third picture is the inside of a gas chamber, where you can still see the blue poison they used, left on the walls and the ceiling. I have so many more pictures from this trip and things to say that are so much more meaningful than a simple “never forget” Please listen to survivors any chance you can. We know the number 6 million isn’t accurate and that it was actually many more sadly. I’m grateful I was able to spend Passover with my family this year, unlike so many who never were able to see their family again, and I am proud to be Jewish. So grateful to @olamimanhattan for making everything possible for me.

Spain 🇪🇸recap part 1 - the non food edition - 🥳 I had such an unbelievable time performing and exploring through Spain last week. Reenacting moments from the Inquisition for almost 1000 young Jews from almost 20 countries as well as everyone passing by was such an incredible and powerful experience and I’m so grateful. Over the course of the week we played over 10 shows, told these stories, and often explained to passing tourists and nuns what we were up to between shows. ❤️🎺🇮🇱

#trumpetplayer #broadwaybaby #chicagoontour #trumpet #leadtrumpet #musicianlife #letsgo #letsgrow #progress #summer #musicianontour #allthatjazz

Finally heading back to NYC and after being here for 3 months I’m definitely feeling all the feels! 🥹 Playing Chicago and living in South Korea all summer has been such an incredible experience and I am so thankful for the opportunity. I’ve learned a lot and grew in so many more ways than I could have imagined both as a musician and a person. I truly feel like I’m a different person than when I got here and it is so nice to head into the fall of new adventures with everything I’ve learned. This summer I truly immersed myself in Korean culture and ate all the things, explored so many fun neighborhoods, and made getting out of the house / off my computer/ and off my horn a huge priority. I hiked over 10 mountains, went to two islands (Nami and Jeju), and since May I have been in 3 countries (Spain, Korea, and Japan). I am only headed back to NYC for another 24 hour stint 🤣 (are you sensing a trend here) but before I describe my next adventure I want to celebrate this one 🙏🏻💕🥳

Happy holidays! 🎉🎺Got some fun performances to wrap up 2023 starting with tonight at 8 pm at Carnegie Hall playing with @thececiliachorusofnewyork and an incredible orchestra premiering an incredible new piece “Everyone, Everywhere” by Daron Hagen using words from articles of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, and from the public statements of Mahatma Gandhi, Senator John Lewis, Frederick Douglass, and Nelson Mandela, among others. Tomorrow I’m out in Queens playing Vivaldi Gloria with a fun group, w some of whom I’ve been playing with for over 10 years. I am also pumped for 12 more shows of Jerusalem Syndrome🙏🏻 various Christmas church services in Brooklyn and Queens, some really fun hiking I have lined up for next week, and a chance to catch my breath now that teaching has paused for the end of the semester. And finally, after playing 6-9 shows a week with only a day or two off per week since May, I’m super excited to start 2024 off by going on vacation 💕
